House Prices - advanced regression techniques

It is often said that: first impressions count! As data scientists, we might then ask what first impressions are made of? Certainly, when looking for a new home the overall appearance of a house plays a big role. But what about the veneer type of the kitchen cabinets or the size of the bath? There are many factors which may influence a purchase. Using a dataset with 79 variables describing homes in Ames, Iowa, we'll look at what really drives house sales.

In this exploration, we will analyze data on house sales and apply advanced regression techniques to answer the following questions:

  • Which factors influence house prices the most?
  • Which neighborhoods if any are most attractive?
  • Which factors are detrimental to a sales price?
  • Finally, can we predict the sales price of a house with reasonable accuracy?

Importing data¶

We will be analyzing the Ames Housing dataset that was compiled by Dean De Cock. It describes the sale of individual residential property in Ames, Iowa from 2006 to 2010 and contains 2919 observations.

alldata = pd.concat((train.loc[:,'MSSubClass':'SaleCondition'],
                     test.loc[:,'MSSubClass':'SaleCondition']))

Univariate Analysis¶

SalePrice¶

'SalePrice' is the target variable that we wish to predict.

In [6]:

Out[6]:

The descriptive statistics summary shows that the minimum price is larger than zero. We also seem to have a maximum price outside the upper quartile indicating the possible presence of outliers.

We now check if the variable follows a normal distribution. This is important because several statistic tests (e.g. t-statistics) rely on this.

In [7]:
sns.distplot(train['SalePrice'], fit=norm);
fig = plt.figure()
res = stats.probplot(train['SalePrice'], plot=plt)
In [8]:
print("Skewness: %f" % train['SalePrice'].skew())
print("Kurtosis: %f" % train['SalePrice'].kurt())

Skewness: 1.882876
Kurtosis: 6.536282

The histogram above shows that SalePrice doesn't follow normal distribution and is skewed right, before performing regression it has to be transformed. We will apply a log transformation to deal with this situation.

Multivariate analysis¶

To reduce confounders, only variables uncorrelated with each other (and correlated with SalePrice) should be added to regression models. We therefore look for multicollinearity in our dataset.

In [9]:
correlation_matrix = train.corr()
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 9))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, vmax=.9, square=True);

Our correlation matrix, visualized on a heatmap, shows there are many strong correlations between variables. As an example, Garage area is strongly correlated with the number of cars, and at the same time both are strongly correlated with the sales price.

There are at least three ways to deal with this issue:

  • Remove confounding variables
  • Use feature engineering
  • Apply dimensionality reduction, reducing the dataset to a smaller number of non-collinear variables.

We now look at the top 10 variables most correlated with 'SalePrice':

In [10]:
n = 10 # Number of variables
columns = correlation_matrix.abs().nlargest(n, 'SalePrice')['SalePrice'].index
correlation_coefficients = np.corrcoef(train[columns].values.T)
sns.set(font_scale=1.25)
hm = sns.heatmap(correlation_coefficients, cbar=True, annot=True, square=True, fmt='.2f', annot_kws={'size': 10}, yticklabels=columns.values, xticklabels=columns.values)
plt.show()
In [11]:
sns.set()
columns = ['SalePrice', 'OverallQual', 'GrLivArea', 'GarageCars', 'TotalBsmtSF', 'FullBath', 'YearBuilt']
sns.pairplot(train[columns], size = 2.5)
plt.show();

We see some non-linear relations with 'SalePrice', e.g. 'YearBuilt'. These may be handled by adding them through some transformation(quadratic etc.) to our regression model. Also note the heteroscedasticity with 'GrLivArea' and 'TotalBsmmntSF' in relation to 'SalePrice'.

Imputations¶

Missing values often have a negative effect on regression/classification models. In addition, some machine learning algorithms, such as Support Vector Machines, can't deal with missing data.

One way of dealing with missing values is to use the mean/mode of the variable to predict the missing values using a regression/classification model. However, being predictions themselves these approaches are not 100% accurate.

In [12]:
total = alldata.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
percent = (alldata.isnull().sum()/alldata.isnull().count()).sort_values(ascending=False)
missing_data = pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Missing', 'Missing/Total'])

Garage¶

We will assume that the garage wasn't built before the house. For the remaning variables, we will assume that NaN's indicate a missing feature or represent some other value.

alldata.GarageFinish.fillna('NoGarage', inplace=True)
alldata.GarageType.fillna('NoGarage', inplace=True)

# Assume garage was built after house
missing = alldata.GarageYrBlt.isnull()
alldata.loc[missing, 'GarageYrBlt'] = alldata.loc[missing, 'YearBuilt']

Transformations¶

SalePrice¶

Our previous univariate analysis showed 'Saleprice' having a positive skewness. Since there are no minimum values of zero, we apply a simple log transform. This also has the benefit of handling outliers.

In [18]:
# Positive skewness - apply a log transform
train['SalePrice'] = np.log(train['SalePrice'])

Total Basement Square Feet¶

fig = plt.figure()

Once again, we find a skewed distribution. Since there are zeros present, we can't simply apply a log transformation. Some more clever engineering is required!

In [25]:
# We create a new variable indicating if the house has a basement
alldata['HasBsmt'] = pd.Series(len(alldata['TotalBsmtSF']), index=alldata.index)
alldata['HasBsmt'] = 0 
alldata.loc[alldata['TotalBsmtSF']>0,'HasBsmt'] = 1

# Log transform data if basement exists
alldata.loc[alldata['HasBsmt']==1,'TotalBsmtSF'] = np.log(alldata.loc[alldata['HasBsmt']==1,'TotalBsmtSF'])

# Histogram and normal probability plot
sns.distplot(alldata[alldata['TotalBsmtSF']>0]['TotalBsmtSF'], fit=norm);
fig = plt.figure()
res = stats.probplot(alldata[alldata['TotalBsmtSF']>0]['TotalBsmtSF'], plot=plt)

Transform skewed variables¶

We check the remaining variables for skewness and apply a log1p transformation as needed.

In [26]:
# Log transform remaining skewed numeric variables:
numeric_columns = alldata.dtypes[alldata.dtypes != "object"].index

# Compute skewness
skewed_features = alldata[numeric_columns].apply(lambda x: skew(x.dropna()))
skewed_features = skewed_features[skewed_features > 0.75]
skewed_features = skewed_features.index

alldata[skewed_features] = np.log1p(alldata[skewed_features])

Simple transform of discrete values¶

We perform one-hot encoding of discrete values.

In [27]:
alldata = pd.get_dummies(alldata)

Check homoscedasticity¶

Homoscedasticity refers to the assumption that the dependent variable exhibits equal levels of variance across the range of values of the independent variable. This is a desirable condition because we want a uniform error term.

We will check homoscedasticity using scatter plots; conical, diamond shapes etc. indicate the presence of heteroscedasticity.

In [28]:
plt.scatter(train['GrLivArea'], train['SalePrice']);

It seems that the log transformations we applied previously have solved this issue!

Normalizing variables - StandardScaler¶

Some machine learning models assume variables have zero mean and unit variance.

In [29]:
alldata[alldata.select_dtypes(['float64']).columns] = StandardScaler().fit_transform(alldata[alldata.select_dtypes(['float64']).columns])

Training and test set¶

Rather than using a common train/dev/test split, we will evaluate our different approaches using n-fold cross validation on the training set.

In [30]:
X_train = alldata[:train.shape[0]]
X_test = alldata[train.shape[0]:]
y_train = train.SalePrice

Error Metric: Root Mean Square Error (RMSE)¶

As our error metric, we choose RMSE since it punishes large errors.

In [31]:
nfolds = 5

def score(model, X, y):
    rmse= np.sqrt(-cross_val_score(model, X, y, scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv = nfolds))
    return(rmse.mean())

Building models¶

Lasso¶

We will use LASSO as our first regression model as it does both parameter shrinkage and feature selection automatically. We use gridsearch to find the optimal alpha.

In [32]:
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

model = Lasso(max_iter=1e5)
alphas = [1e-4, 1e-3,1e-2, 1, 5, 10]
grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv=5, param_grid=dict(alpha=alphas)) #, n_jobs=-1

grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

print((-grid.best_score_)**0.5)
print(grid.best_estimator_.alpha)

# Create a LASSO model with best alpha
model = Lasso(alpha = grid.best_estimator_.alpha)
# Do cross validiation using our optimal model
print('RMSE: ' + str(score(model, X_train, y_train)))
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

0.124070499644
0.001
RMSE: 0.123082892524

Gradient Boosting¶

Some of the variables in our dataset have many outliers. One benefit of using gradient boosting together with the huber loss function is that it provides good robustness to outliers. In addition, by setting max_features to sqrt we reduce the overfitting of our model.

In [36]:
from sklearn import ensemble, tree, linear_model
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_squared_error

model = ensemble.GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=3000, learning_rate=0.05, max_depth=3, max_features='sqrt',
                                               min_samples_leaf=15, min_samples_split=10, loss='huber').fit(X_train, y_train)

print('RMSE: ' + str(score(model, X_train, y_train)))

RMSE: 0.122723443617

We gained a slight improvement over LASSO!

Predicting house prices¶

We now turn to predicting the house prices in the test set.

In [37]:
y_test = model.predict(X_test)

X_test = X_test.assign(Prediction=pd.Series(np.exp(y_test)).values)
In [38]:
neighborhoods_stacked = X_test.filter(regex=r'^Neighborhood_', axis=1).stack()
neighborhoods = pd.Series(pd.Categorical(neighborhoods_stacked[neighborhoods_stacked!=0].index.get_level_values(1))).apply(lambda x:x.split('_')[1].strip())

X_test = X_test.assign(Neighborhood=pd.Series(neighborhoods).values)
In [39]:
locations = pd.read_csv('neighborhoods.csv')

X_test = pd.merge(X_test, locations, how='left', left_on='Neighborhood', right_on='id')

Visualizing predictions¶

Finally, we plot our predictions on a map.

In [40]:
def floatRgb(mag, cmin, cmax):
    # Normalize to 0-1
    try: x = float(mag-cmin)/(cmax-cmin)
    except ZeroDivisionError: x = 0.5
    HSV = ((x + 1)/2, 1, 1)
    RGB = colorsys.hsv_to_rgb(*HSV)
    return RGB

def rgb(mag, cmin, cmax):
    red, green, blue = floatRgb(mag, cmin, cmax)
    return int(red*255), int(green*255), int(blue*255)

def strRgb(mag, cmin, cmax):
    return "#%02x%02x%02x" % rgb(mag, cmin, cmax)
In [41]:
neighborhoods = X_test.groupby(['name', 'lat', 'lon'])['Prediction'].agg({'price': ["count", "mean"]})

map_lat = locations.describe().lat['mean']
map_lon = locations.describe().lon['mean']

house_map = folium.Map(location=[map_lat, map_lon], zoom_start=13)

max_salesprice = neighborhoods.max(numeric_only=True)['price', 'mean']
min_salesprice = neighborhoods.min(numeric_only=True)['price', 'mean']

max_salescount = math.log(neighborhoods.max(numeric_only=True)['price', 'count'])
min_salescount = math.log(neighborhoods.min(numeric_only=True)['price', 'count'])

# Add circlemarkers
for i in neighborhoods.iterrows():
    lat = i[0][1]
    lon = i[0][2]
    priceheat = strRgb(i[1]['price', 'mean'], min_salesprice, max_salesprice)
    countradius = 35 * (math.log(i[1]['price', 'count']) - min_salescount) / (max_salescount - min_salescount)
    fontsize = str(int(32 * (math.log(i[1]['price', 'count']) - min_salescount) / (max_salescount - min_salescount)))
    popup_html = '<h3><center>' + i[0][0] + '</center></h3>' + 'Average sales price: ${:,.2f}'.format(i[1]['price', 'mean'])
    iframe = folium.IFrame(html=popup_html, width=150, height=100)
    popup = folium.Popup(iframe, max_width=2650)
    
    folium.Marker([lat, lon],
                  icon=DivIcon(
                    icon_size=(1,1),
                    icon_anchor=(countradius/1.4,countradius/1.1),
                    html='<div style="font-size: ' + fontsize + 'pt;font-family: Impact, Arial"><center>' + '{:.0f}'.format(i[1]['price', 'count']) + '</center></div>',
                    )
                 ).add_to(house_map)
    
    folium.CircleMarker(location=[lat, lon], radius=countradius,
                    popup=popup, color=priceheat,
                    fill_color=priceheat).add_to(house_map)

# Add map title
folium.map.Marker(
    [42.058936037037033, -93.693046777777784],
    icon=DivIcon(
        icon_size=(200,36),
        icon_anchor=(0,0),
        html='<div style="font-size: 24pt;font-family: Brush Script MT">The City of</div>',
        )
    ).add_to(house_map)

        icon_anchor=(0,0),
        html='<div style="font-size: 44pt;font-family: Impact, Arial">Ames</div>',

    ).add_to(house_map)

  • The numbers inside the circles show the number of sales in that neighborhood
  • Blue and red colors, indicate respectively, a low and a high average sales price.

Conclusions¶

Naturally, the amount of living area has the greatest influence on the sales price. The four neighborhoods Crawfoord, Stone Brook, Northridge, and Northridge Heights also have a positive impact on sales price.

One interesting factor is the exterior material covering the house. A brick face seems to be the most attractive material. Another factor is the zoning classification of the home where a commercial or mixed housing type is least attractive.

We have shown how regression models can be applied and tuned in order to answer our initial questions and predict house prices. One avenue of exploration could be to create a per-neighborhood-model to answer more local questions. This could reveal in which neighborhoods certain characteristics, such as a certain exterior type, are most appreciated.
